<div id="review_753064118" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/753064118" />
    <a title="Timothy Riley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4996855-timothy-riley"><img alt="Timothy Riley" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/753064118?book_show_action=true">Oct 30, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Timothy Riley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Timothy Riley" href="/user/show/4996855-timothy-riley">Timothy Riley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4996855-timothy-riley?shelf=society">society</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4996855-timothy-riley?shelf=civil-war-reconstruction">civil-war-reconstruction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4996855-timothy-riley?shelf=race-relations">race-relations</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4996855-timothy-riley?shelf=travel">travel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer753064118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18019793665962107657">If you read my reviews, by now you will see they frequently have an anti-southern tinge to them. This one won&apos;t disappoint either. This was a well researched book that takes readers through modern day civil war sites, cities, forts and battlegrounds. The title doesn&apos;t quite fit the book; however,mainly because the main theme is not so much these southerners who want to fight the war all over again but how the history of this time period is reinvented to fit people&apos;s philosophies. For the South i</span>
  <span id="freeText18019793665962107657" style="display:none">If you read my reviews, by now you will see they frequently have an anti-southern tinge to them. This one won't disappoint either. This was a well researched book that takes readers through modern day civil war sites, cities, forts and battlegrounds. The title doesn't quite fit the book; however,mainly because the main theme is not so much these southerners who want to fight the war all over again but how the history of this time period is reinvented to fit people's philosophies. For the South in general it is a war that still resonates. It was not difficult for Horwitz to find neo-confederates who curse yankee scum, support segregation and reminisce about the "good old days" of before the northern assailants stole their "freedoms" and told them how to "live their lives". Readers should figure out on their own what those phrases mean, but a search for these people doesn't make for a good challenge or a book for that matter. <br />It is very clear that starting in the early 20th century when most of the veterans from that war were dying off, the south began turning the conflict into a mythical tale of southern glory. That is when the majority of the monuments went up and racial hatred took another turn for the worse. <br />The war itself is used to continue to polarize the nation even more than it did in the late 19th century. There are plenty of stories of veterans from both sides participating together in memorial, marches, and reenactments with grace. Sadly their kids and grandkids can't bury the hatchet. <br />Two more points: there are more Nathan Bedford Forrest monuments than all other confederate leaders combined as well as his modern day merchandise out sells Lee's 5 to 1. Considering that Lee was flawed but still a "southern gentleman" and Forrest founded the KKK and was responsible for the slaughter of unarmed black soldiers at Fort Pillow, this shows how southerners took the most extreme and most hateful legacy to carry forward. They will dig in their heals against change if he is their hero from the war. <br />Modern southerners all through the book used the language and somtimes exact quotes of the Civil Rights Movement to champion their cause. They say "change is gonna come" and "free at last" concerning liberal and northern oppression (no one can articulately explain what rights have been stolen). 13,000 northern soldiers died at Andersonville prison camp in Georgia in two years. The head of the camp Henry Wirz has an annual memorial service in the town and is viewed as a martyr because he was hung after the war for war crimes. That's insane. </span>
  <a data-text-id="18019793665962107657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


