    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_868843768" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/868843768" />
    <a title="Quo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7392004-quo"><img alt="Quo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1393910036p2/7392004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/868843768?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Quo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Quo" href="/user/show/7392004-quo">Quo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7392004-quo?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7392004-quo?shelf=personal-identity">personal-identity</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7392004-quo?shelf=societal-struggle">societal-struggle</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer868843768" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4553778793301179947">Tony Horwitz offers a non-academic view of the differences that serve to make the original Confederate states, many of today&apos;s &quot;red states&quot; different from the rest of the nation and from each other, a rather fascinating overview of the American South that is rather unconventional but quite interesting.<br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1626059015i/31622089.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>Horwitz goes on the road in search of interesting characters, letting them provide defining commentary, rather than attempting to tell his own story to or redefine more formal historical accounts o</span>
  <span id="freeText4553778793301179947" style="display:none">Tony Horwitz offers a non-academic view of the differences that serve to make the original Confederate states, many of today's "red states" different from the rest of the nation and from each other, a rather fascinating overview of the American South that is rather unconventional but quite interesting.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1626059015i/31622089.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Horwitz goes on the road in search of interesting characters, letting them provide defining commentary, rather than attempting to tell his own story to or redefine more formal historical accounts of the southern part of America.<br><br>For starters, he becomes involved in a Civil War battle reenactment with an absolute purist, bent on living the era, dealing with conditions approximate to those a Confederate or Union soldier might have had to deal with, adopting the uniform, jargon &amp; even temperament of a battle-weary soldier at the time of the Civil War, even including the precise stitching technique that would have been used to sew on a uniform button at that time &amp; place.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1626058963i/31622085._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>There are many surprises in the way those Horwitz encounters define themselves and interestingly some seem to promote an anti-Federalist approach to government, much as others did in the early days of the American Republic, with the author sensitive to the political &amp; social feelings of those he intersects with while traveling through the South. <br><br>There are few stereotypes of good old boys, latter day rebels espousing the KKK or garbed in the Confederate flag. Instead, to cite one example, there is a fellow who hand sews Confederate flags &amp; is definitely an individualist following a different path but who is the son of a Yale University professor, is married to a woman from Columbia (S. America) &amp; raising children of mixed heritage., not exactly the profile of a latter day Johnny-Reb. There are many similar examples that do not fit conveniently into old molds for those who live south of the Mason-Dixon Line.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1626058963i/31622086._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I've read several books by Tony Horwitz and met the author at a local gathering/book signing event. His approach to writing does not involve classic historical accounts but rather causes one to feel a part of a travel adventure, with Horwitz as a kind of laid-back guide. Sadly, Tony Horwitz died in May 2019 at age 60.<br><br>*Within my review are 2 images of the author, the 2nd in the midst of a Civil War reenactment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4553778793301179947" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


