<div id="review_3404770392" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3404770392" />
    <a title="Stephen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4809022-stephen"><img alt="Stephen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1295019472p2/4809022.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3404770392?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen" href="/user/show/4809022-stephen">Stephen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3404770392" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4434735690023311700">I’m really interested in the American civil war of late after reading books on Stonewall Jackson, Grant and all of Shelby Foote’s trilogy and watching the Ken Burns series. Looking at it from the outside in the UK, I think it explains a lot of why America today is as it is although as the book says at the end “a high proportion of our population was not even in this country when the War was being fought”. So I found this fascinating and have ordered the author’s later book too. It is tragic that</span>
  <span id="freeText4434735690023311700" style="display:none">I’m really interested in the American civil war of late after reading books on Stonewall Jackson, Grant and all of Shelby Foote’s trilogy and watching the Ken Burns series. Looking at it from the outside in the UK, I think it explains a lot of why America today is as it is although as the book says at the end “a high proportion of our population was not even in this country when the War was being fought”. So I found this fascinating and have ordered the author’s later book too. It is tragic that he died so young last year - an update now would really help to see if things are really changing. But when this was written it’s not a very encouraging story with black and white leading very separate lives with very different perspectives - almost an artificial segregation even though that went years ago. <br /><br />Someone who wasn’t a Civil War enthusiast and as familiar with the various battles and protagonists might not enjoy this as much as me - they could tire of reading about yet another civil war reenactor as there are a lot of those in here. But for me it was great and I learnt a lot, some of it giving a different view of things I thought I knew - eg that a statue of Arthur Ashe the tennis player sits amongst those of Lee, Jackson etc in Richmond’s Monument Avenue. There’s even an interview with Shelby Foote where he comes across very differently from in the Ken Burns series. It’s also put me on to new areas to research such as Andersonville and Nathan Bedford Forrest.<br /><br />Highly recommended for everyone wanting to better understand modern day America and a must read for anyone with an interest in the Civil War.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4434735690023311700" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


